rah Lee/Sarah Lee","mediaId":"733d156d87fbeff3c893c3ff6abded72f1710dd2","picdarUrn":"GD*33416357","width":"2060"}}]}],"id":"stage/2015/jul/07/rebecca-lenkiewicz-interview-ida-the-invisible-jane-wenham-witch-walkern","sectionId":"stage","webTitle":"Rebecca Lenkiewicz: this government is 'determined to crush the poor'","references":[],"webPublicationDate":"2015-07-07T08:43:38Z","fields":{"liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>At first glimpse there isn’t much of a connection between a play set in the 1700s about a woman who has been hanged as a witch and one about legal aid cuts in the 21<sup>st</sup> century. But playwright <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/jan/20/rebecca-lenkiewicz-playwright\">Rebecca Lenkiewicz</a> is certain that there is – and not just because her name is on the front page of both plays. <a href=\"http://www.outofjoint.co.uk/production/jane-wenham-the-witch-of-walkern\">Jane Wenham: The Witch of Walkern</a> (opening later this year at Watford Palace and then on tour) and <a href=\"https://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/event/the-invisible/\">The Invisible</a> (now at the Bush theatre in west London) are set worlds and centuries apart, but both explore communities under pressure and the age-old tendency to start witch-hunting. Lenkiewicz is confident now is one of those times.</p> <p>“I’m deeply troubled about the way society increasingly talks about the poor and less fortunate. There’s such a shift from when I was young,” says Lenkiewicz who is now in her mid-40s. “The language used is so scary, the talk of those on benefits as being ‘manipulative’ or human beings described as ‘cockroaches’. The fact that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/apr/30/katie-hopkins-life-harder-disabled-people\">Katie Hopkins</a> has a page in the Sun. That kind of language is spreading and fast. It’s terrifying.”</p> <p>Language is Lenkiewicz’s currency. An actor turned playwright, she has a remarkable facility for words in performance, possibly because she knows about the pleasure of speaking lines that are textured, full of possibilities and don’t always give up their meanings too easily. She loves actors, saying they are the ones who “are on the front line”, and admiring the way they can bring “insight and clarity” to what she has written. “Sometimes you know that what you’ve written is a bit pedestrian and it becomes something completely other because of their interpretation.” She still misses acting. “I would do it again if I could, but I’ve lost the muscle. I’d want to be brilliant at it and I’d fall short.”<br /></p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/jan/20/rebecca-lenkiewicz-playwright\">Playwright Rebecca Lenkiewicz: 'I had evil thoughts as a child'</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Falling short is not something Lenkiewicz has much experience of as a writer. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/mar/10/nicholas-hytner-national-theatre-director-12-years-verdict\">Nicholas Hytner</a> is a fan, talking of her “tremendous gift for dialogue”. Hytner programmed two of her plays while he was running the National Theatre – including her second play, the Chekhovian Irish family drama <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2004/aug/04/theatre1\">The Night Season</a>, and the suffragette epic <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2008/aug/02/theatre1\">Her Naked Skin</a>, the first original play by a living female writer to be staged in the Olivier. </p> <p>On stage, her dialogue dances. Face to face, she’s quite reticent, perhaps as result of being too unguarded about her personal life to journalists in the past, and the fact that her first play, in 2000, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2000/aug/07/artsfeatures.edinburghfestival20002\">Soho: A Tale of Table Dancers</a>, grabbed the headlines for all the wrong reasons because it was inspired by her own – very brief – experience of table dancing. But she can also be unexpectedly and disarmingly open, too.</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KL5nE_j5GsU\"                                                                        > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/KL5nE_j5GsU?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>   <p>“I feel very raw,” she suddenly says at one point during the conversation when we are talking about The Invisible and Jane Wenham and their emphasis on “the other” and those who fall outside society’s boundaries of conformity. “Maybe it’s because I’m at the halfway point in my life, when you are thinking about the ground you’ve made and the ground you haven’t, but I feel very sensitised to what’s happening and this fear of otherness and push towards conformity. Feeling raw is not a pleasant feeling, but it can be a fruitful feeling.”</p> <p>For a writer, certainly. She draws on that rawness in both plays. In Jane Wenham, developed with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/may/27/max-stafford-clark-interview-out-of-joint-arts-funding-british-theatre\">Max Stafford-Clark</a> for Out of Joint, she writes about women in all their complexity, beauty and unflinching cruelty, focusing on women who are viewed as outsiders, and particularly “men’s terror” of such women. As the title suggests, The Invisible is about those whom we prefer to leave hidden from view and whose safety nets are being steadily dismantled by the current government.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2000/aug/07/artsfeatures.edinburghfestival20002\">Arts: Rebecca Lenkiewicz interviewed</a> </p> </aside>  <p>The Invisible is a Bush commission, and when Lenkiewicz went in to have an initial meeting with <a href=\"https://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/about-us/the-team/\">artistic director Madani Younis</a> she was confident that she would turn it down because she had so many other projects bubbling under. But when she heard the extent of the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/law/2014/sep/25/-sp-legal-aid-forgotten-pillar-welfare-state-special-report-impact-cuts\">cuts to legal aid – in 2013-14 43,000 fewer people</a> in England and Wales were granted legal aid to be represented in court – she instantly said yes, feeling she had to do something, and speak up about a situation where, increasingly, those on lower incomes are being denied access to legal advice.</p> <p>Law firms such as the one in The Invisible, which take on legal-aid cases, are closing because they simply cannot make enough money to pay overheads and salaries. Even criminal justice is affected: last month, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/law/2015/jun/25/lawyers-to-refuse-criminal-cases-in-protest-at-cuts-to-legal-aid-fees\">solicitors and barristers threatened strike action in Liverpool</a> after incurring a further reduction of 8.75% in legal-aid fees in the wake of a 17.5% cut last year.</p> <p> “People are being punished for being poor,” Lenkiewicz says indignantly. The Invisible tells the human stories behind the statistics rather than dealing in the statistics themselves. “Every time I put in a statistic, it felt like a clunk. So now audiences are going to be given leaflets after the play that have all the facts and figures.”</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MS72tYfGn0Y\"                                                                        > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MS72tYfGn0Y?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>   <p>She’s aware that writing a play is not necessarily going to change the government’s mind and that it is “a cry in the wilderness”, but she refuses to stand by and be silent about “a government that is determined to crush the poor and vulnerable. All I can do is shout loudly about it. A play may be a very small ripple, but it’s a start.”</p> <p>In February this year Lenkiewicz was at the Oscars where <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/sep/25/ida-pawel-pawlikowski-nun-road-movie\">Ida</a>, the film she co-wrote with Paweł Pawlikowski about a novice nun in 1960s Poland, won the award for best foreign language film. She is currently working on another film script, about the second world war <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/the-womens-blog-with-jane-martinson/2012/oct/23/noor-inayat-khan-britains-muslim-heroine\">allied spy Noor Inayat Khan</a>, who worked as a radio operator in Nazi-occupied Paris and was arrested and sent to Dachau, where she was executed, apparently with the word “Liberté” on her lips. “That’s what we all want: freedom. The freedom to be ourselves, that’s my mantra,” says Lenkiewicz quietly.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3b32f23e1e24c97d95701757c96888f3084878a6\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436195762660/139e88bd-7536-4f91-8794-129e75d2d46f-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Ida, film still\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Agata Kulesza in Ida, which Rebecca Lenkiewicz co-wrote with Paweł Pawlikowski.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Being in Los Angeles was a thrill because she has always been movie-mad – she remembers seeing <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/nov/13/les-enfants-du-paradis-review\">Les Enfants du Paradis</a> at the Electric Cinema in Portobello Road, London, as a seven-year-old with her father. But she recognises that something like the Oscars is “only a punctuation, a lovely moment of euphoria” in a life dedicated to the writing.</p> <p>“I love writing. For me, the real joy is the writing process itself. Everything that comes after is an adventure and it can be joyful and sometimes painful, but it’s set apart from the work. What I love is finding the idea, and then that moment when the piece starts to speak to you. That’s the fertile time. The dirt of the work is where I’m at my most confident. Just being in the mud and trying things out.”</p> <ul> <li><a href=\"https://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/event/the-invisible/\">The Invisible is at the Bush theatre</a>, London, until 15 August. <a href=\"http://www.watfordpalacetheatre.co.uk/page/144/Jane-Wenham-The-Witch-of-Walkern/1153\">Jane Wenham: the Witch of Walkern is at Watford Palace</a> from 23 September to 3 October, then <a href=\"http://www.outofjoint.co.uk/production/jane-wenham-the-witch-of-walkern\">touring until 30 January</a><br /></li> </ul>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"The Oscar-winning co-writer of Ida is determined to shout loudly about cuts to legal aid. The result is her new drama, The Invisible. ‘A play may be a very small ripple,’ she says, ‘but it’s a start’","headline":"Rebecca Lenkiewicz: this government is 'determined to crush the poor'","byline":"Lyn Gardner","commentable":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4adt7","wordcount":"1209","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436197407687/030f343a-8349-42d5-953c-5f9ec74de804-140x84.jpeg","commentCloseDate":"2015-07-10T09:45:00+01:00","standfirst":"<p>The Oscar-winning co-writer of Ida is determined to shout loudly about cuts to legal aid. The result is her new drama, The Invisible. ‘A play may be a very small ripple,’ she says, ‘but it’s a start’</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/jul/07/rebecca-lenkiewicz-interview-ida-the-invisible-jane-wenham-witch-walkern","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/stage/2015/jul/07/rebecca-lenkiewicz-interview-ida-the-invisible-jane-wenham-witch-walkern","sectionName":"Stage","tags":[{"id":"stage/theatre","webTitle":"Theatre","type":"keyword","s