carpet, Tatum was responding to comments by his friend and 10 Years co-star Chris Pratt about gender equality in Hollywood. “I think it’s appalling that for a long time only women were objectified,” <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jun/19/jurassic-worlds-chris-pratt-equality-means-objectifying-men-too\">Pratt said in a recent interview for Jurassic Park</a>. “I think if we really want to advocate for equality, it’s important to even things out.”</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/06/channing-tatum-magic-mike-xxl-chris-evans-chris-pratt-teen-adult-actors\">The evolution of Channing Tatum: from 'dull beefcake dude' to XXL movie star</a> </p> </aside>  <p>The equality drive was in full force at Sydney’s Qantas Credit Union Arena where, despite the chilly temperatures, crowds of mostly female fans turned out to meet Tatum and his co-star Joe Manganiello, and hashtag their brief encounters.</p> <p>Some had camped out overnight to secure a carpet-side spot. To a soundtrack of Backstreet Boys, Nelly and Usher, they brandished homemade banners saying: ‘‘I want to Channing on your Tatum” and “Joe makes my heart go”. One fan held up a sign proclaiming “1,000km travelled to see you Chan”, while her male partner jiggled a toddler behind her. Across the carpet, a group of manicured VIP guests clambered over the media barriers to get a better look at the actors.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"16cfc6439b82b4d97f8ee3a94aa8ba4a48fba25b\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/16cfc6439b82b4d97f8ee3a94aa8ba4a48fba25b/0_146_3500_2102/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Joe Manganiello during the ‘Magic Mike XXL’ Australian premiere at the Qantas Credit Union Arena on Monday, July 6, 2015, Sydney. (AAP Image/Gaye Gerard) NO ARCHIVING\" width=\"1000\" height=\"601\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Joe Manganiello meets his fans.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Gaye Gerard/AAP</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Manganiello, more circumspect than Tatum on matters of objectification, said men were more likely to feel appreciation for the attention thrown their way. “It takes so much work to prep and get in the gym and learn those routines, and train the way we do,” he said. “To me it’s work and we’re being appreciated for the work that goes into it.”<br /></p> <p>As the author of the motivational bodybuilding guide <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Evolution-Cutting-Breaking-Mental-Building-ebook/dp/B00BSBR4MM\">Evolution: The Cutting Edge Guide to Breaking Down Mental Walls and Building the Body You’ve Always Wanted</a>, Manganiello said he enjoyed roles that required him to work out, even Magic Mike XXL’s partly nude scene. “You’re playing a character that is not self-conscious, so for you to be self-conscious in that scene wouldn’t make sense.”</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/06/magic-mike-xxl-attracts-women-scares-men-box-office\">Magic Mike is an XXL hit with women but why did it turn men off?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Magic Mike XXL is a follow-up to Steven Soderbergh’s surprise 2012 indie hit Magic Mike, about a group of male strippers. The sequel sees Magic Mike (Tatum) reunited with his Kings of Tampa colleagues for a road trip to a stripping convention. Despite heavy marketing, the second film grossed only <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/06/jurassic-world-magic-mike-terminator-genisys-box-office\">$28.7m over its first weekend in the US</a>, compared with the original’s $39.1m opening.</p> <p>While Tatum and Manganiello signed photographs and posed for selfies with the Sydney fans, a group of topless male dancers flexed their pecs and gyrated down the red carpet in Magic Mike-branded threads. Inside the</p> <p>The film’s producer, Reid Carolin, a longtime Tatum collaborator, told Guardian Australia: “Men in Hollywood are used to being able to fit into any kind of role that they’d like to [while] women, whether playing a stripper or an everyday woman, have this pressure to fit a certain body type.” </p> <p>Carolin hoped Magic Mike XXL sparked discussion about body image. “We are objectifying men and saying women can look at men the same way men have been looking at women on screen for years.” </p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/video/2015/jul/07/magic-mike-channing-tatum-sydney-australia-red-carpet-video\"            data-short-url=\"http://gu.com/p/4aexa\"                    data-show-ads=\"true\"            data-video-id=\"2332837\"            data-video-name=\"Magic Mike XXL star Channing Tatum: ‘I’ve plumbed the depths of my life as a stripper’ – video\"            data-video-provider=\"AAP\"            data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/7/1436226716248/Channing-Tatum-Mike-Sydne-003.jpg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-457423819\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/7/1436226716248/Channing-Tatum-Mike-Sydne-003.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2015/07/07/150707magicmike_FromGAus-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2015/07/07/150707magicmike_FromGAus.webm\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2015/07/07/150707magicmike_FromGAus_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2015/07/07/150707magicmike_FromGAus/150707magicmike_FromGAus.m3u8\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2015/07/07/150707magicmike_FromGAus_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source> </video> <figcaption>Channing Tatum on the Sydney red carpet for Magic Mike</figcaption> </figure>   <p>Although he wouldn’t label Magic Mike a feminist movie – <a href=\"http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/07/magic-mike-gender-sex-politics-roundtable/397385/\">as some media outlets have done</a> – Carolin said it did treat women as independent characters, “people with their own voice [who] aren’t there to service the men in the movie”. He added: “I also hope that it shows women of all different body images.”</p> <p>Tatum and Carolin have worked together on both Magic Mike films – co-writing this sequel – as well as collaborating on 22 Jump Street, White House Down and 10 Years. They are currently co-producing the superhero flick, Gambit, and then hope to co-direct an as-yet-undecided project. Carolin hinted at a joint project about daredevil Evel Knievel.</p> <p>Tatum said of their ongoing partnership: “We got started making and producing films because we weren’t seeing films that we wanted to be in and be a part of.”</p> <ul> <li>Magic Mike XXL opens in Australian cinemas on 9 July <br /></li> </ul>","productionOffice":"AUS","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"The Magic Mike XXL star says it’s time for men to be objectified too, as thousands of female fans oblige at the film’s Australian premiere in Sydney","headline":"Channing Tatum on Magic Mike XXL: 'I’m all for equal opportunity objectification'","byline":"Alexandra Spring","commentable":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ae2q","wordcount":"742","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d335d5d44efd7ba52f737b953b940466042f3e82/0_72_1936_1162/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-07-10T14:00:00+10:00","standfirst":"<p>The Magic Mike XXL star says it’s time for men to be objectified too, as thousands of female fans oblige at the film’s Australian premiere in Sydney</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/07/channing-tatum-on-magic-mike-xxl-im-all-for-equal-opportunity-objectification","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/jul/07/channing-tatum-on-magic-mike-xxl-im-all-for-equal-opportunity-objecti