"displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198004311/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-300x180.jpeg","source":"Dan Tuffs","photographer":"DAN TUFFS","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Gong show: Danny Elfman in his studio in Los Angeles.","height":"180","credit":"Photograph: DAN TUFFS/Dan Tuffs","mediaId":"80b9d54e57973d36a1e2a89446c026c96c4f844d","picdarUrn":"GD*38708694","width":"300"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198004447/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-380x228.jpeg","typeData":{"copyright":"Dan Tuffs (commissioned)","displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198004447/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-380x228.jpeg","source":"Dan Tuffs","photographer":"DAN TUFFS","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Gong show: Danny Elfman in his studio in Los Angeles.","height":"228","credit":"Photograph: DAN TUFFS/Dan Tuffs","mediaId":"80b9d54e57973d36a1e2a89446c026c96c4f844d","picdarUrn":"GD*38708694","width":"380"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198004589/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-620x372.jpeg","typeData":{"copyright":"Dan Tuffs (commissioned)","displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198004589/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-620x372.jpeg","source":"Dan Tuffs","photographer":"DAN TUFFS","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Gong show: Danny Elfman in his studio in Los Angeles.","height":"372","credit":"Photograph: DAN TUFFS/Dan Tuffs","mediaId":"80b9d54e57973d36a1e2a89446c026c96c4f844d","picdarUrn":"GD*38708694","width":"620"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198004999/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-2060x1236.jpeg","typeData":{"copyright":"Dan Tuffs (commissioned)","displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198004999/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-2060x1236.jpeg","source":"Dan Tuffs","photographer":"DAN TUFFS","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Gong show: Danny Elfman in his studio in Los Angeles.","height":"1236","credit":"Photograph: DAN TUFFS/Dan Tuffs","mediaId":"80b9d54e57973d36a1e2a89446c026c96c4f844d","picdarUrn":"GD*38708694","width":"2060"}}]}],"id":"film/2015/jul/06/danny-elfman-tim-burton-lincoln-center-festival","sectionId":"film","webTitle":"Danny Elfman: 'It was the most intense fear I've felt in my career'","references":[],"webPublicationDate":"2015-07-06T17:04:30Z","fields":{"liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p><a href=\"http://www.johnmauceri.com/\">John Mauceri</a> had an idea. He had conducted the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra for 16 years, and was well-versed in the music of films. He and composer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/02/danny-elfman-tim-burton-singing\">Danny Elfman</a> had worked together when Mauceri had conducted the orchestra on some of Elfman’s work from his long, illustrious, almost symbiotic relationship with director <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/video/2014/dec/19/tim-burton-on-big-eyes-a-weird-symbolic-version-of-the-american-dream-video-interview\">Tim Burton</a>. The music got Mauceri thinking: what if they mixed Burton’s artwork, fresh from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2010/mar/11/tim-burton-moma-exhibition\">a retrospective at Museum of Modern Art in New York City</a>, with the music it inspired?</p> <p>According to Mauceri, Elfman had never been particularly comfortable with live performance of his orchestral works. “He records it, supervises it, produces it, and then moves on to something else.” But when they approached Elfman about the multimedia performance, to Mauceri’s surprise, Elfman said yes.</p> <p>Elfman says that when he was approached to do the stage concert, he was both excited and terrified. (A feeling he was used to: after he sent the score for Pee-wee’s Big Adventure – the first collaboration between Elfman and Burton – the composer was convinced Warner Brothers would simply throw his work in the trash never to be heard again.) “I had been approached about doing these concerts for 20 years, but I didn’t have time. It was too much work – I didn’t like thinking backwards,” Elfman said. “But then I finally thought: ‘It’s now or never.’”</p> <p>The resulting show, which is factually if not eloquently titled <a href=\"http://www.lincolncenterfestival.org/2015/danny-elfman-s-music-from-the-films-of-tim-burton\">Danny Elfman’s Music from the Films of Tim Burton</a>, had popular runs in London, Los Angeles and Tokyo, and will finally come to New York City, taking over Lincoln Center from 6-12 July. The show features music from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/frankenweenie\">Frankenweenie</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/87108/beetlejuice\">Beetlejuice</a>, <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0099487/reference\">Edward Scissorhands</a> and many more films rearranged by Elfman to be performed by a live orchestra, paired with a series of visual images chosen by Burton himself, and with the composer stepping into the limelight to sing highlights from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/17/musical.timburton\">The Nightmare Before Christmas</a>.</p> <p>For Mauceri, Elfman’s willingness to sing was a sign of his commitment to the project. “That changed everything,” Mauceri said. “It gave the concert a kind of imprimatur of the composer, who’s actually there, performing his music, and having arranged it, and trusting us to interpret it.”</p> <p>That wasn’t the only surprise that Elfman had in store for Mauceri. “Danny himself decided that he would create the orchestral suites that we would play. He did not farm it out to other people; he did not use pre-existing materials that orchestras might have played over the years.” </p> <p>The only problem was that Elfman had no idea how to compose an orchestral suite. That had never stopped him before, though. “I had no music lessons and no training. I came in out of the blue, which is why I caught so much shit in Hollywood for so many years,” Elfman said. “When I first started writing songs with Tim for Nightmare Before Christmas, neither of us had any clue how to make a musical. We just started doing some songs. Starting on this stage show was like that. I just started.”</p> <p>He carved out four months from his packed schedule and set about reconfiguring some of his best-known film scores – <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0089791/reference\">Pee-wee’s Big Adventure</a>, <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0096895/reference\">Batman</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/feb/25/alice-in-wonderland-film-review\">Alice in Wonderland</a> and The Nightmare Before Christmas among them – for the orchestra. “I didn’t know what the correct way to do anything was,” said Elfman, who transformed 15 film scores into suites to fill a two-hour performance. “It was a great challenge and the big surprise was that it wasn’t a disaster.”</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7jMGp41cTEY\"                                                                        > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/7jMGp41cTEY?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption>Danny Elfman and co perform.</figcaption> </figure>   <p>As he worked, he quickly realised that some of his scores, like Alice in Wonderland, were easy to translate, but earlier works like Pee-wee’s Big Adventure and Beetlejuice were much more difficult to sculpt into orchestral suites. “They needed to be taken apart, because they didn’t work just being plunked on the stage,” said Elfman. “I had heard parts of Batman, Beetlejuice, and Pee-wee in other concerts and generally I hated them. The first time I heard Pee-wee live on stage, I realised half of it was piano and the strings were just sitting there. In the film it’s fine, but onstage there’s nothing happening. I had just never imagined playing it live.”</p> <p>Now Elfman knows there is a different way to approach writing for film as opposed to writing for concerts. “The best way I can describe it is if I have a whole orchestra playing, but I want to hear a single clarinet, on a film I just move up a microphone. In a concert, I have to carve out the space for it to play within the 85 pieces of orchestra surrounding it. I really had to reconceive each piece to get the energy of what we hear coming out of the speakers on the screen into the concert.”</p> <p>Finally, Elfman was done. With the show arranged, the team headed to London for the premiere. Elfman, though, had not been able to actually hear his suites performed yet. He finally heard an orchestra play his suites two days before the London premiere, but there was no time to make any changes other than to rectify a few printing errors. </p> <p>“I had no idea if it was going to work on any level. And I had flippantly agreed to sing. I hadn’t sung in 17 years! I had never even sung the songs all the way through,” he says. “It was the most intense fear I had ever felt in my career, but Helena Bonham-Carter was there to sing Sally’s song and she said: ‘I know what you’re thinking, but just fuck it.’ I thought about it and said: ‘Yeah, that’s what I’ve been doing my whole life,’ and I went out there and did it,” Elfman said. “I thought I would have to win over the London audience, but they were great. It is one of the most moving live experiences I’ve had.”</p> <p>When Danny Elfman’s Music from the Films of Tim Burton comes to Lincoln Center for its run of shows, opening night will mark his 25<sup>th</sup> concert. So Elfman has worked out his performance anxiety, although playing in front of a New York audience comes with its own set of nerves. “I haven’t played in New York since that USO show I did for the troops in world war two,” joked Elfman. “So I haven’t played in New York in a long time. I hope they’ll be kind.”</p> <ul> <li>Danny Elfman’s Music from the Films of Tim Burton conducted by John Mauceri will be part of <a href=\"http://www.lincolncenterfestival.org/2015/danny-elfman-s-music-from-the-films-of-tim-burton\">the Lincoln Center Festival</a> from 6-12 July<br /></li> </ul>","productionOffice":"US","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"Famous for composing the scores for Tim Burton’s films, the musical genius had always shied away from doing live concerts – until now","headline":"Danny Elfman onstage: 'It was the most intense fear I've felt in my career'","byline":"Melissa Locker","commentable":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4adjg","wordcount":"1098","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/6/1436198003947/2ffa278f-2f1d-4e0b-9909-8f9fba2579fd-140x84.jpeg","commentCloseDate":"2015-07-09T13:00:00-04:00","standfirst":"<p>Famous for composing the scores for Tim Burton’s films, the musical genius had always shied away from doing live concerts – until now</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/06/danny-elfman-tim-burton-lincoln-center-festival","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/jul/06/danny-elfman-tim-burton-lincoln-center-festival","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/film","webTitle":"Film","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/film","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/film","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"music/music","webTitle":"Music","type":"keyword","sectionId":"music","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/music/music","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/music/music","sectionName":"Music","references":[]},{"id":"culture/cultu